2 Lotka-Volterra

2.1 Model

We start by defining a function, which depends on the vector of variables u, parameters p and time t.

\[ \begin{gather} \frac{dx}{dt} = \alpha x - \beta xy \\ \frac{dy}{dt} = \gamma xy - \delta y \end{gather} \]

Note
  • ẋ represents the instant change in the population of \(x\), the prey over time.
  • ẏ represents the instant change in the poupulation of \(y\), the predator over time.
  • α is the rate of growth of the prey.
  • β is the rate at which predators kill prey.
  • γ is the rate of growth of predators due to killing prey.
  • δ is the rate of death of predators.
function lotka!(du, u, p, t)
  x, y = u
  α, β, γ, δ = p
  du[1] = dx = α*x  - β*x*y
  du[2] = dy = γ*x*y - δ*y
end;

2.2 Parameters

We specify the value of the parameters, the initial conditions and the time span.

lotka_p = (α = 0.1, β = 0.005/60, γ = 4e-5, δ = 0.04)
lotka_u0 = [200, 600]
lotka_tspan = (0.0, 360.0);

2.3 Simulation

lotka_prob = ODEProblem(lotka!, lotka_u0, lotka_tspan, lotka_p)
lotka_sol = solve(lotka_prob, reltol=1e-8, abstol=1e-8);

We find the vector with times in .t:

3 Kermack and McKendrick

3.1 Model

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \frac{dS}{dt} &=& -\beta IS \\ \frac{dI}{dt} &=& \beta IS - \gamma I \\ \frac{dR}{dt} &=& \gamma I \end{eqnarray} \]

function sir!(du, u, p, t)
  S, I, R = u
  β, γ = p
  du[1] = dS = - β*I*S 
  du[2] = dI = β*I*S - γ*I
  du[3] = dR = γ*I
end;

3.2 Parameters

sir_p = (β = 0.01, γ = 1/8)
sir_u0 = [200, 1, 0]
sir_tspan = (0.0, 90.0);

3.3 Simulation

sir_prob = ODEProblem(sir!, sir_u0, sir_tspan, sir_p)
sir_sol = solve(sir_prob);

3.4 Visualisation

sir_df = DataFrame(sir_sol)
rename!(
  sir_df,
  :value1 => :Susceptibles,
  :value2 => :Infectious,
  :value3 => :Recovered
)
sir_melt = stack(sir_df, Not(:timestamp))
sir_melt |> head

4 HIV multi-compartmental model

4.1 Model

\[ S = e^{-\delta_1 t} + \frac{1}{\gamma} e^{-\delta_2 t} \]

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \frac{dV_b}{dt} &=& k_{lb} V_b - c_b V_b \\ \frac{dV_l}{dt} &=& S - k_{lf} Vl + k_{fl} V_f - c_l V_l \\ \frac{dV_f}{dt} &=& k_{lf} V_l - k_{fl} V_f \end{eqnarray} \]

function sl!(δ, γ, t)
  exp(-δ*t) + (1/γ) * exp(-0.001*t)
end;
function hiv!(du, u, p, t)
  Vb, Vl, Vf = u
  klb, klf, cl, cb, kfl, δ, γ = p
  du[1] = dVb = klb*Vl - cb*Vb
  du[2] = dVl = sl!(δ, γ, t) - klf*Vl + kfl*Vf - cl*Vl
  du[3] = klf*Vl - kfl*Vf
end;

4.2 Parameters

hiv_p = (klb=0.5, klf=0.033, cl=3, cb=4.4, kfl=0.21, δ=0.44, γ=50)
hiv_u0 = [1, 20, 80]
hiv_tspan = (0.0, 2.0);

4.3 Simulation

hiv_prob = ODEProblem(hiv!, hiv_u0, hiv_tspan, hiv_p)
hiv_sol = solve(hiv_prob, reltol=1e-8, abstol=1e-8);

4.4 Visualisation

hiv_df = DataFrame(hiv_sol)
rename!(
